In [[mathematical logic]] and [[computer science]], '''Gabbay's separation theorem''', named after [[Dov Gabbay]], states that any arbitrary [[temporal logic]] formula can be rewritten in a [[Logical equivalence|logically equivalent]] "past&nbsp;→&nbsp;future" form. I.e. the future becomes what must be satisfied.<ref>{{citation|title=Handbook of Temporal Reasoning in Artificial Intelligence|volume=1|series=Foundations of Artificial Intelligence|first1=Michael David|last1=Fisher|first2=Dov M.|last2=Gabbay|first3=Lluis|last3=Vila|publisher=Elsevier|year=2005|isbn=9780080533360|page=150|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ajsvo6jWNhgC&pg=PA150}}.</ref> This form can be used as execution rules; a [[MetateM]] program is a set of such rules.<ref>{{citation | last1 = Kowalski | first1 = Robert A. | last2 = Sadri | first2 = Fariba | contribution = Towards a Unified Agent Architecture That Combines Rationality with Reactivity | doi = 10.1007/BFb0031739 | isbn = 3-540-61814-7 | pages = 137–149 | publisher = Springer-Verlag | series = [[Lecture Notes in Computer Science]] | title = Logic in Databases: International Workshop LID '96, San Miniato, Italy, July 1ÔÇô2, 1996, Proceedings | volume = 1154 | year = 1996}}.</ref>
